iet; Cordova.\n11*4al3V\nCATTLE MARKETS.\nut'ui vnnir\nxian xuuix.\nNEW YORK, October 8?Rccves-RcCdpts.\n821 head. No trading. Pressed\nbeef steady. No later cables. Exports,\n81\". cattle and 2,?46 quarters of beef.\nCalves?Receipts. 658 head; market\nSteady. Veals. 8.00a 11.00; culls. ,\"i.H0a6.*i0;\nWesterns. 6 35; crassers. 3.00. Dressed\ncalves steady; rity dressed veals, 11a17t?;\ncountry dressed, 0*%al3; dressed prassers\nand fed calves. 8alo.\n8heep and lamba?Receipts, 3.1 til head\nSheep ?teady; lambs. 25c hisrlier. Sheep.\n3.00*4.25; lambs. 6 25a7.30: culls, 3.o??a?.00.\nHogs?Receipts, 1,532 nominal; quotations,\n9.15aO.50.\nCHICAGO.\nPlIICACJO, ?)rtober H.?Cattle? Receipts.\n1.0OO head; market steady; beeves. 4.7??a\n8.06; Texas steers. 3.40a5.73; western\natcers. 4.00a6 75; stoekers and feeders.\n4.25*5.85; co*s and heifers, 2.25a6.-f<>;\ncalves, T.OOalO.OO.\nHoj?s? Receipts. 13.000 head; market. 5c\nlower than early; liRht. 8 45aJ>.10: mixed,\n8.10*9.05: heavy, 8.00a.s.N5; rouRh. 8.00a\n8.20; rood to choice heavy, 8.20a8.85; pigs,\n8.20*9.00; bulk of sales. 8.40*8.75.\nSheep?Receipts. 2.000 head; market\nteady; native, 2.50*4.40; western. 2.75a\n4.25; yearlings. 4.35a5.50; lambs, native,\n4.80a7-15; western. 4.75*7.00,\nNEW YORK MINING STOCKS.\nNF.W YORK. October 8.\nAlk-e 2.00\nCVnutock Tunael Stock 21\nOomsteek Tunnel Bonds. offered 19\nCon. Col. ood Vo\nHorn Sltrrr 37\nIron SllTcr 1.30\nTesdvlll* Con 03\nI.ittlc Chief 08\nMexican SO\nOntario 2.33\nSS\nStandard to\nYellow Jacket Sk>\nManchester Cloth Market.\nMANCHESTER. October 8?The settlement\nof the lockout failed to brins\nIncrease.! order* for cloths, and the salet\nfor the week were again small and con\nfined to miscellaneous assortments foi\nMediterranean and South American mar\nkets and home trade centers. Buyers\nfor India and China were not dispoeet\nto pa>* the higher prices asked.\nTarns were firm and from to 'i<\nhigher. The sales made during the loch\nout depleted stocks and made spinner:\nBarder to deal with.\n\nFDfAHCIAL.\n1\nUnder Super\nIssue\n\nou are saving money and ar<\nworld;\nre not saving any money an<\n1 pauper all your life.\nit to be?\n?ly don't want to have to\nition all your life?to be at\none else?to be subject to d\nn anv time and all the time.\niven't already opened a Sa\\\ne and add to it consistently\n:r let a pay day go by withe\n:count.\nCompound Intere\non Savings Accoi]\nBAflMGS\nand Mass.\nBranches:\nits. N.E. 436\ni\nfflSBEEagggsfrftfrrt\nCHICAGO GRAIN.\nCHICAGO. October 8.?Expectation of\nn substantial increase Monday in the\nvisiblo supply of wheat operated to prevent\na rise in prices t??day. Moreover,\nArgentine news was less unfavorable\nas to ttic crop oullook. The close was\nlower to 't higher than last night.\nCorn finished 'ia1* to M up. and oats\nunchanged to 14 advance. There was\na net decline of 10c to 25c in liog\nproducts.\nUnlooked-for support developed in the\nwheat pit during the last hour of trading.\nRumors of Greece recalling her\nrepresentative at Constantinople and\nof a frost visitation in Argentina\nwere the causes, hut neither story was\nconfirmed, anil indications that the total\namount of wheat in sight throughout\nthe l'nited States would show enlargement\nproved a decided weight on\nquotations near the end of the session.\nEarlier In the day rain was reported\nIn a portion of drought-stricken Argentina.\nand there was selling of cargoes\nfrom that country at Liverpool. Kuroi\npean markets were generally lower in\nconsequence, and tli^ bearish effect was\nfelt here.\nShorts, however, were timid and were\ninduced to rover when dispatches from\nMinneapolis told of the mills there being\nfree buyers of both futures and cash.\nThe close was steady at intermediate\nfigures. I'e^etiiber ranged trom t'7%\nORUaOS-'Si. finishing 1i net lower, at 0814-\nThe corn market tightened up when\nearly sellers tried to buy back. Such\ndealers had apparently overestimated the\nInfluence of the fine weather and the\neasier cables. December fluctuated between\n40 and 40%. with the last sales\n%a>4 up. at 40'/j. Corn cash was steady\nto 14 lower. No. 2 yellow closed at 52\na 52%.\nIn oats there was much covering by\nshorts of the larger sort- Primary receipts\nwere a million bushels less this\nweek than a year ago. I>ecember sold\nbetween \"2Ha.12\\ and 33, closing at exactly\nlast night's figures, 52%.\nWith hogs weak and support lacking,\nprovisions sagged all day. Final quotations\nwere off 12*6 to 25c; lard, 10 to\n22%a25c, and ribs, 10al2Vs to 27Vie.\nFRUIT MARKET,\nNKW YORK. October 8.?Evaporated\nj apples are quiet with a small jobbing\n1 trade; on the spot fancy is quoted at\n,10: choice, 8a?a;c?: prime, 8a8:;t; com.\nmon to fair, 6%a7,-4.\nPrunes are quiet but steady; quota|\ntions range from ,r>alO for California\nj up to 30-8?s and 7%aIt's for Oregons\nfrom 60s-20s.\nApricots are inactive and steady;\nchoice, 11-%allV&; extra choice, 12V&al3;\nfancy, 13%al 4.\nPeaches are dull and barely steady.\nChoice, 7a7Vi; extra choice, 8a8Vi;\n1 fancy, SViaf.\nRaisins are steady, but the demand is\nsmall; loose muscatels are quoted at\nr?'tak for 2a5 crown; choice to fancy\nseeded, 6%a8; seedless, 5at5; London\nlayers, 1.20a 1.35.\nDry Goods Market.\nNEW YORK, October S.?The cotton\ngoods market continues steady and\nstrong. Fruit of tbe loom 4-4 and\nbleached sheetings have been sold out,\nand orders will now be taken on value\nonly. Yarns are firmer. LU>cns mlo\nstrong. Burlaps are in active demand.\nROAD COMMISSION SCORED.\nGrand Jury Objects to Condition of\nBaltimore Pike.\nSpecial Dispatch t?> Th<* Star.\nCUMBERLAND. Md? October S.-Thc\ngrand jury in its report to the court today.\nsays:\n\"In the matter of the condition of the\nBaltimore pike, leading from Cumberland\nto the Six-Mile House, we would say\nthat, in our opinion, the state road commission\nlias shown an entire lack of competence\nin directing the work on the road.\n\"For over a year and a half the citizens\nof our county have not been able to\nuse the road, of the utmost importance to\none of the best farming regions in western\nMaryland. Farmers have been unable\nto move their crops.\n\"Incapable men have been put in\ncharge. Contractors have failed to fulfill\ntheir contracts In our opinion, the\nstate road commission has sat supinely\nby and allowed our citizens to suffer.\n\"If the road is nqt placed in ?-ondttion\nfor travel by the time the next grand\njury convenes we would recommend that\neach member be indicted for the gross\nnegligence which lias been shown.\n\"Knough money lias been spent, from\nwhat we can learn, to have completed\nthe work. The same money seems to\nhave been frittered away, and no result\nhas been accomplished.\"\nState W. C. T, U. Elects Officers.\nSpecial Diseati-U to The Star.\nCHARLESTON. W. Va October 8\nj The W. C. T. I*, in state convention here\nelected the following officers: President,\nMrs. Lena Lowe Yost, Morgantown; vice\npresident, Mrs. Jennie Everett Engle,\n4 Elkins; secretary, Mrs. J. Walter Barnes,\nI Fairmont; treasurer. Mrs. A. J. Clienoweth.\nElkins: L. T. L. secretary, Mrs.\n1 A. T<aw*rence. Charleston; musical di\nrector, Mrs. William E. Bowman. Wheol?\ning; core winding secretary, Mrs.\nWan 'lie Pickering, Rowlcsbarg.\n|_ FIHAHCIA1,\nvision of the U. S. Treasury. P\ns going to get\ni are going to\n)ccupy a sub- g\nthe beck and 3\nlismissal from S\n4 H\nrings Account g\nY and persist-\n)ut increasing\n!St 1\nints. S\nBANK,\n/e. N.W. I\n7th St.S.W. 1\nFOREIGN MARKETS.\nLONDON, October 8?The stock market\nstarted the week dull and hesitating,\nhut after temporary weakness closed firm\nand cheerful. The Portuguese revolution\ncaused uneasiness in the foreign' section,\ntvith a loss of throe points in Portuguese\nbonds, but as Paris took the news calmly\nand sent Jirm advices later the effect in\nother directions soon disappeared. The\nsatisfactory settlement of the Manchester\ntrouble and good traffic returns induced\na broadening demand for home\nrails and industrial stocks, while buyers\npicked up rubber shares more freely on\nthe better prices obtained at the raw\nrubber auction. Reinvestment of dividend\npayments helped giit-edged securities,\nbut consols closed only an eighth\nhigher.\nAmerican securities were generally firm,\nbut quiet. Temporary setbacks on poor\npnttnn rrnnrfg artH Knn r n rp??l 1 r?? uprp\noffset by better metal reports, and tlie\nprospect of a more favorable New York\nbank statement made llnal prices about\ni a point higher on the week.\nMoney continued in fair supply and discount\nrates weakened on rumors of gold\ncoming from Brazil. Money and discount\nrates were easy today.\nThe stock market was quietly cheerful.\nRubber and oil shares and foreign bonds\nhardened, and gilt-edged securities and\nhome rails were maintained. Kaffirs\nclosed dull.\nAmerican securities opened steady, but\nsupport was lacking and prices receded\na fraction from the best.\nTrading was light, and the market\nclosed quiet.\nBERLIN, October 8.?Tradffig was dull\non the bourse today.\nPARIS, October 8.?Prices were weak\non the bourse today on reports of a revolution\nin Albania and fear of complications\nbetween Turkey and Greece.\nWANTS MINE RESCUE STATION.\nGeorges Creek Region Selected as\nSite by Representative Pearre.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCUMBERLAND. Md., October 8?Representative\nGeorge A. Pearre is making\nI an effort to secure the establishment of a\nj mine rescue and investigation station in\nthe George's creek coal region in Maryland.\nlie wrote J. A. Holmes, director of\ni the bureau of mines, setting out the wis1\ndom and necessity of establishing such a\nstation in Maryland, which would bo\ni available for the bituminous coal field of\nPennsylvania In the neighborhood of Meyersdalo\nand the doal tields of West Virginia\nin the neighborhood of Elkins and\nThomas. Congress appropriated ?110,000\nfor the establishment of such stations in\nthe various coal tields, and Col. Pearre\nbelieves one of them ought to be located\nin this neighborhood.\nDirector Holmes, in reply to Mr. Pearre's\nJotter, says: \"I wish it were possible,\neven out of the current appropriation, to\ncarry out your wish in the establishment\nof a mine rescue station in the George's\ncreek field, but prior to my appointment\nthe allotment for mine rescue stations in\nthe different coal fields had already been\nmade, and it is not possible now to consider\na change. If during the next session\nof Congress ihc mine rescue work gieets\nwfth sufficient approval I hope we may be\nable to arrange either for a station in\nthe George's creek region or for a mine\nrescue ear, which would spend a considerable\nportion of its time in that region,\nvisiting the different important mining\ncenters.\n\nCHINESE JOINTS RAIDED.\nOpium Worth $1,000 Confiscated by\nChicago Police.\nCHICAGO, October s.?Three Chinamen\nwere arrested and $1.ooo worth of opium\nwas confiscated in eight raids on \"joints\"\nin Clark street, Chicago's \"Chinatown,\"\nlast night. Twelve government officers\nfrom the internal revenue and the United\nStates marshal's offices took part in the\nraids.\nSontp of the places raided were crowded\nwith Chinese gamblers when the government\nofficers rushed in after knocking\ndown \"lookouts\" who were stationed at\nthe front. Ignorant of the meaning of\ntiie raids and surprised by the entrance\nof the officers, the Chinamen fled into the\nstreets.\nLascars Celebrate in Boston.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nBOSTON, Mass., October 8.?Weird cer;\nemonies were conducted aboard the Brit1\nisli steamship Katuna, t'apt. Lee, front\nCalcutta and Colombo, when the forty or\nmore Lascars composing the freighter's\ndeck and fireroom forces last Thursday\ncelebrated the feast of Rhadam by absolutely\nrefusing to work. Next day was\ngiven over to feasting, chanting and\npompous display.\nNew Russian Minister of Education.\nST. PETERSBURG, October 8.?It is\nI gemi-umciany announced that Dr.\nSchwartz has resigned the portfolio of\ntlte ministry of education, and that M.\nKasso, director of Katkoff Lyceum, at\nMoscow, has been appointed his sucnHor;\nUPLIFT LOOKED REAL\nGenuine Coloring to Week's\nBull Campaign in Market.\nPUBLIC LURED TO STREET\nGave Insiders an Opportunity to Unload\nSurplus Holdings.\nBANKS VETO BIG MOVEMENT\nNot in Position to Finance Stock\nMarket Operations on Vast Scale.\nThe Business Outlook.\nBy W. G. Nicholas.\nSpecial Correspondence of The Star.\nNEW YORK, October 8, 1010.\nThe game was played so strong that a\nlot of genuinely bullish sentiment was\ndeveloped in the stock market and the\npublic came in on a larger scale than at\nany time in months. On the rise insiders\nin various pools and cliques got rid\nof a very considerable line of securi\ntics, both bonds and stocks.\nThere was an appearance of the real\nthing about the later stages of the\nrally and many really wise and experienced\npeople were led to believe that\nthe movement might have substantial\nbasis and that It meant something besides\nthe usual line of buncombe, guff\nand bluff. The rise was pushed along\nsteadily from about the date of the\nMaine election, and in some of the\nleaders the advance amounted to 8 or\n10 points, Reading scoring the most\nimportant improvement among the\nactive issues. It moved up 10 points.\nUnion Pacific advanced points, Baltimore\nand Ohio 5^4, Chesapeake and Ohio\n8, Atchison 4 points,' and the other\nstocks along the list from 2 to 3 points.\nThe standards were slowest to get\nunder way and only covered about 2\npoints.\nIn actual ground covered Western\nUnion was the star performer, making a\ngain of 14 points, but that was really\nan exception which placed It in a\nclass by Itself. The rally represented\na reawakening of a stock long dead in\na speculative sense. It came in response\nto a realising sense that Western\nUnion ex-Gould was a much more\nvaluable proposition than it ever had\nbeen while under the control of the\nformer regime.\nAwaiting on Digestion.\nIf it is shown that the market can absorb\nand stow away the 1,000,000 Shares\nor more of inside stock that was unloaded\non the advance the manipulators may put\nthrough ahother upward whirl. The mar-\nket is.just now g??ng through the process\nof assimilation,' and the immediate\nfuture of prices depends on how\nthoroughly and how easily the Job is\ndone.\nThe banking syndicates have still remain-\ning on hand large quantities of goods\nwhich they would like to unload, and if\nthey see they can induce the public to\nstay awhile around current prices or\nhigher the same dear, delightful public\nwill be given opportunity to Increase its\ncargo. Take the caso of steel as an\nexample of how things are done. It\nwas quietly shoved up from around 07\nto 70*4, not a very large or suspicious\nadvance, but a pretty good thing after\nall, in the face of a very bad industrial\nsituation and enough to attract outside\ntrade on the exchange. All at once\nt he stock had a burst of unusual activity.\nThe first three days of this week\nit was traded in to the extent of about\n300,000 shares within the price range of\n(BlVj. and 7<H?. The bulk of the transactions\nwere within of a point of 70;\nthen the .price broke off sharply to 00, and\nthe manipulators sat back to see how\nthe game would work out. The enormous\ntrading mentioned was construed\nas distribution. By no stretch of the\nimagination could it be tortured into\naccumulation. Somebody was getting rid\nof the stuff in a wholesale way and the\ncunning professionals on the exchange\nfeel very -sure inside sources can supply\nany sort of demands that may develop\naround these prices.\nSteel Folks Optimistic. u\nRepresentatives of the iron and fiteel n\ntrade have strangely worked themselves Jj\nup toto quite ah optimistic frame of\nmind With overproduction of pig iron t\nstaring them in the face, with orders h\nfalling ofT and all the big consumers buy. b\ning only what they have to the visible out-\nlook is discouraging, yet the large manu-\nfacturers, including the steel trust and\nleading independents, have gotten tlieir\nheads together and decided that it would\nbe possible to maintain prices and that all\nthey had to do was to sit tight to get the\nbusiness.\nThe iron trade has these fits sometimes. lf\nOccasionally the hunch is right; some- d\ntimes it isn't, and when it isn't there is d\nalmost always an uncomfortablj state of ,v\ndemoralization in the industry. The\nsteel trust and most of the independents\nare running on (55 to 67 per cent of ca- Jj\npacity, but when this is stated it must\nbe borne in mind that the 65 to 67 per ei\ncent is on a capacity nearly, lf not quite,\ndouble what it was six years ago. From\nthat angle is doesn't look so bad. C]\nThe trust will probably show earnings P\nfor the third quarter close to $35,000,000.\nThat would make $115,000,000 for the P\ntirst nine months ol the year. If the net\nfor the last quarter should not be above\n$50.000,000 there would still be a net ci\nshowing of $145,000,000 for the year, g\nThat is away below January expectations, n\nbut it would nevertheless he about $60,000,000\nabove the fixed charges, and $45,- t(\nOOn.OOO after dividends arc paid on the ti\ncommon stock. There would be left over n\nfor surplus and extraordinary expend!\ntares a kingly sum, although in view of n\nthe heavy outlays for extensions and new\nplain it could not be expected that surrtlnu\nnnn 1H hn in 11 r? Vi if utl V thp frftlliPr\npl>?0 VUIVI ?'V 11> I l| m J v?. v. gn aaava\nIndeed, It would not be at all surprising\nif the corporation did not have to eat into w\nIts enormous cash surplus, which now if\nfigures somewhere around >133,000,000. J,\nU. P. Needs Money. p\nThe street fcas been full of bear talk ti\n011 Union Pacific. President Jxivett is h\nquoted as saying that the Union Pacific\nsystem would have to put through >130,- v\n000,000 in new financing within a year,\nalthough it is supposed to be earning j,\nvast sums over and above current re- C\nquircments for maintenance, dividends n\nand interest. These exuberant statements e\nQ\nof current prosperity do not some way\nharmonise with the glutinous demands for\nnew money.\nThe Hill stocks are none too strong, but\nthere seems to have recently developed\nquite a friendly feeling for Atchison.\nSomething is expected from the Interstate\ncommerce commission very soon on that\nsuspended order for a reduction on moun-\ntain rates, and that something can hardly\nbe bulllBli, even though there should J}\nbe further extension of the time of grace.\nWith the Increased population and ton- ,i\nnage in the far west there cannot be\nmuch more delay in the beginning of a u\ncontinuous era of reduced rates from the\nexorbitant and oppressive figures which\nhave so long ruled in that part of the\ncountry.\nBanks Discourage Speculation. I\nThe banks help along these little minor\nbull campaigns, but they give it out cold\nand flat that they will not be parties to 4\nthe encouragement of broad speculative\nactivity which would impose Upon them ti\nthe necessity of heavy financing. Their\nchief interest in the stock market now c\nis to aid in finding a market. for some\nof the collateral with which they are\nloaded down for account of favored clients.\nWhen speculative activity gets beyond'that\nstage they pull in their horns.\nThey have no money either now or in\nprospective tip to the end of the year for\nI lie financing of a big gamble in stocks. S\nThe surplus reserve is now down to a u\nslii't-'t .111c! and Ihtit M s^Pflb'Uf\" t.y'l-k 1\nWEEK'S RANG\n\nCorrected to the Close of\nthe New York S\nRailway and Misc\nThe following table shows the week'\nIndividual sales and net changes of sec\nExchange last week. High and low pf\n11)09 and the year 1910 to date:\n??190#??* f 1910\nHigh. Low. Hlgb. Low.\n984 05 !M>% 554 Amal. Copper\n764 44Vi 724 \\594 Am. Car Fdry.\n<94 42'* 09% 524 Am. C