ere Is very little interest beng\ntaken in the campaign so far as\nTince George county in the fifth district\n3 concerned. Thomas Parran. thr? re\nubllcaq nominee, has held no meetings in\nhe county, and up to this time but one\nlub has been organized in his behalf?\normed a few nights ago in Riverdale for\nhe main purpose of getting all eligible\nepublicans on the registration books. The\nlub will hold weekly meetings at the old\n!alvert mansion in Riverdale, and a committee\nhas been named to arrange a rally\nIther in that town or in Hyattsvllle.\nThe Chilium Democratic Club, located\nti the home district of J. Enos Ray, jr.,\nhe democratic candidate, is doing some\nrork, and inaugurated the campaign for\n?r. Ray last Monday evening, wnen a\nmass meeting was held at Mount Rainier,\n'he Hyattsvllle. Democratic Club, many\nf whose members opposed the nominalon\nof Mr. Ray, has indorsed the canidate,\nand committees are now at work\nettlng prospective voters on the regisrattoii\nbooks. This evening Mr. Kay\npoke at a mass meeting held ih Masonic\ntali, Hyattsvillc, but the inclement\nrcather kept the attendance down.\nVANT NO TOWN HALL BUILT.\nlyattsville Ex-Councilmen Ask\nCourt to Stop It.\npedal CorretDondence of The Star.\nUPPER MARLBORO, October S, 1010.\nA biH filed In the equity court here by\nFranke Rushc and William A. Brooks,\normer members of the common council\nf 'Hyattsvilie, seeks to _ restrain the\ntayor and common council from acquirlg\nland and borrowing money with\nrhlch to erect a municipal building.\nu?c i<iukn>euiuii iu erect a building for\nhe use of the town and the Are departlent\nhas created considerable discussion\n1 the town. Mayor Magruder and Counilmen\nFainter and Burgess voted against\nhe town purchasing land and borrowing\nloney for this purpose. Councilmen A.\nGreager, Edward Devlin, Stephen J.\n[elly and E. A. Fuller voted for ordiances\nto purchase property from Dr. H.\nWillis and to borrow money from the\n[yattsville Building Association.\nThe court will hear arguments on inlnction\nthe first part of November.\n11\nArgentine Ship at Philadelphia.\nPHILADELPHIA, October 8.-Carrying\nwenty-flve cadets in addition to its otters\nand crew, the Argentine training\nhip Presidente Sarmiento arrived here\n>day from New Orleans. Interest is\ndded to the visit of the vessel, whleh\ni of the cruiser type, by reason of the\nact that the New York Shipbuilding\nompany is constructing, at its plant\nn the Delaware river, a battleship of\nreadnought proportions for the Argenne\nRepublic. The cadets Will be given\nn opportunity to inspect the big wartip.\nHUNTERS, HOUNDS AND\nFLEET-FOOTED FOXES\nTriple Combination Warms the I\nSporting Blood in Montgomery\nCounty, Xd.\nSpecial CorreaoondeDce ?f The Star. j\nROCKVILDE. Md., October 1010\nAbout thirty of the beet known fox\nhunters of Montgomery county assembled\nin Rockvilie about 3 o'clock this morning.\nand three hours later were enjoying a\nsplendid chaae In the vicinity of Seneca,\nthirteen miles above Rockvilie.\nAlmost immediately after the hounds?\nthirty-two in number?were turned loose\na trail was struck, and before they could\npack a second trail was encountered, and\nthe dogs separated with the result that\ntwo chases were on at the same time.\nFor more than two houra the foxes were\nkept on the move, the two packs of dogs\nbeing in full cry the entire time. Things\nfinally became so hot that the foxes made\nup their minds, about the same time\nevidently, that to seek the protection of\ntheir dens would be the part of discretion\nand they \"ran in.\"\nHounds Again Give Tongue.\nThe dogs were called off, and within a\nvery few minutes another fox was started.\nHe. however, did not display the\ngamcness of the others and after a hot\nhalf-hour chase sought his den.\nBy this time the rain was falling steadily,\nwith no signs of letting up, and the\nhunt was called off for the day.\nAmong those who enjoyed the sport\nwere James P. Gott, Edmund C. Davis.\nJohn C. Bentley, Edward C. Peter. Charles\nA. Clagett, Andrew J. Cummlngs. Michael\nOumminge. Clay Edwards. Bradley\n_ 1 M.I ni t Dai.Io U'aK.\nV_ rt I I UUilU iJTWIO, AlUCll DUUK, CWstor\nSpates. Oeorge Poole. Joseph Howes,\nWilliam Riggs, Charles J. Eyddane, Dr.\nChambers, Oeorge Kclchner, Edward\n(Welsh, hVederlck Allnutt, Samuel D.\niByrd. Ooorgc Allriutt, W. O. Spates,\nSamuel Welsh and numerous residents of\nthe Seneca neighborhood.\nOBGAN BOLTS HABMOH.\nDemocratic Paper in Ohio Befuses to\nSupport Governor.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nCINCINNATI, Ohio, October 8?The\nPaulding Times, one of the influential\ndemocratic newspapers in that democratic\nterritory, has bolted the nomination\nof Judson Harmon for re-election as\ngovernor of Ohio. It opposes Harmon\non the ground that Harmon opposed\nBryan in his three presidential campaigns\nand that he is a man whose every act\nas chief executive of the state hks shown\nthat he is in sympathy with corporations\nand their interests.\nThe Times charges that predatory and\nreactionary interests are backing Harmon\nfor governor. It is further asserted that\nWall street is back of Harmon's presidential\ncandidacy.\nWliile the Times carries the democratic\nstate tickeb at the head of its editorial\npage it omits the name of \"Judson Harmon\nfor governor.\"\n\nEDUCATIONAL.\nIN WASHINGTON.\nMrs. Dougal-Marcon, L. Mus,\nTF.ACHER OF PIANO.\nGraduate of Detroit School of Miwic and Windsor\nConservatory pf Music. Canada.\nRF.SIDKXCB STUDIO. I7rw RfOOS PI,. N'.W.\nMISS JULIA R. GOODALL,\nTeacher in pianoforte and theory of tDUflc.\nPupil of tJctaarwenka of Berlin.\noc3-30t*,4 Studio, ft-ta P at. n.w.\nMBSDF.MOISELLES MARKT. NATIVE FRENCH\nteai'liera (diploma). Private inatruction and\nclasses. Translation work In English. Preach,\nGerman. Italian and Spanish, lilt 13th i.w.\noc3-14f.4\nFRENCH LANGUAGE,\nDiction, elocution. literature.\nPROF. C. G. RIVOT. Offlcier d'Acsdeaslo,\nTHE CUMBERLAND, Thomas Circle.\nocl-30t*\nMoun